<CaseStudy slug="ai-ops-workflow">
  <p class="lead reveal">AI coding agents are capable and unreliable at the same time. They'll happily ship broken work, skip the checks, and forget what they were doing between sessions. So I built a layer around one: a set of rules, hooks, and a few review agents that make its output safe enough to act on.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The system</h2>
  <p class="reveal">It's a governance layer for an AI coding agent. It adds tiered process, safety hooks, persistent memory, and structured review by separate agents. The point is to get from "the model did something" to "the work is checked and stayed in scope." I use it every day on my own builds, including this site.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">How it works</h2>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Guard hooks for dangerous actions.</strong> A deny layer catches irreversible operations (secret reads, force-push, destructive deletes) before they run. The policy lives in code, not in a prompt.</li>
    <li><strong>Adversarial review by separate agents.</strong> On higher-stakes changes, independent reviewer agents are spawned to try to refute the work. A finding only survives if it holds up, and a plain serial pass catches what the structured one misses.</li>
    <li><strong>Done means evidence.</strong> "Done" isn't a claim here. A stop-gate looks for real proof (test output, a build exit code, a screenshot) before anything counts as finished.</li>
    <li><strong>Effort matches the stakes.</strong> Small changes move fast; risky ones get the full process. Typed memory keeps goals and decisions intact across sessions so the work doesn't drift.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why it matters for AI work</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The hard part of running agents in production isn't whether they're capable. It's whether they're reliable, safe, and checkable. This is a working example of all three: limited autonomy, guardrails that are actually enforced, and a bar for "done" that needs evidence. It's the same approach I'd bring to running agents on a team.</p>
</CaseStudy>
